<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1986" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Ophiomyia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ophiomyia virginiensis" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="virginiensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ophiomyia virginiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be characterised by a strongly pronounced furrow on the facial bulb, the ultimate and penultimate sections of M4 are equal in length, the basiphallus is mostly composed of a single narrow band, and the distiphallus is large with discrete sections, including a high, internally smooth subtriangular basal section.
</paragraph>
